class GraphNode {
  int value;
  List<GraphNode> neighbors;  //normally, ArrayList
}

List<GraphNode> graph;

V (vertex) = number of nodes
E = number of edges

0 <= O(E) <= O(V^2)

Comparison: For linked list and tree, O(E) == O(V)

A sparse graph is one where |E| = O(|V|) or less

  • Most ‘real world’ graphs are sparse
  • Transportation networks, WWW, Mazes, Facebook, integrated circuits, etc.

按密級程度分:

  • Dense Graph
  • Sparse Graph

Representations of a graph

- unweighted (有權重圖) weighted (無權重圖)
directed (有向圖) - -
undirected (無向圖，可以理解為雙向) - -

Adjacency matrix vs. Adjacency list (更常見)

Adjacency Matrix:

boolean[][] matrix = new boolean[V][V];
int[][] matrix = new int[V][V];

Adjacency List:

List<GraphNode> graph;

class GraphNode {
  public int value;
  public List<GraphNode> neighbors;
  public List<Integer> weights;  //make sure the i'th integer is the weight of the edge to the i'th node in neightbors
}

Example 1. Directed, unweighted

Adjacency Matrix

source\target a b c d
a 0 1 0 0
b 0 0 1 0
c 1 0 0 1
d 1 0 0 0

Adjacency List

a -> <b>
b -> <c>
c -> <a, d>
d -> <a>

list:

Example 4. Undirected, weighted

Adjacency Matrix

source\target a b c d
a 0 2 -1 9
b 2 0 3 0
c -1 3 0 8
d 9 0 8 0

Adjacency List

a -> <(b,2), (c,-1), (d,9)>
b -> <(a,2), (c,3)>
c -> <(a,-1), (b,3), (d,8)>
d -> <(a,9), (c,8)>

degree(x) represents how many neighbors x has

  • in degree
  • out degree

Space Complexity

  • Adjacency Matrix Representation: [O(|V|^2)]
  • Adjacency List Representation: [O(|V| + |E|)]
  • Which is the better choice if the graph is dense? (Same; Matrix slightly better)
  • Which is the better choice if the graph is sparse? (List better)

How expensive it is to answer whether there is an edge from u to v?

  • Adjacency Matrix Representation: [O(1)]
  • Adjacency List Representation: [O(degree(u))]

DFS: Depth First Search (先走深)
BDS: Breadth First Search (先走寬)

深度優先,用Queue實現

public List<Integer> levelOrderTraverse(TreeNode root) {
  if (root == null) {
    return null;
  }
  List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
  Queue<TreeNode> queue = new ListedList<>();
  queue.offer(root);
  
  while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
    TreeNode curr = queue.poll();
    result.add(curr.key);
    if (curr.left != null) {
      queue.offer(curr.left);
    }
    if (curr.right != null) {
      queue.offer(curr.right);
    }
  }
  return result;
}

print: {1} {3 2} {5 4 7} {9 11} {13}

public List<Integer> levelOrderTraverse(TreeNode root) {
  if (root == null) {
    return null;
  }
  List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
  Queue<TreeNode> queue = new ListedList<>();
  queue.offer(root);
  
  while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
    int size = queue.size();
    List<Integer> currList = new ArrayList<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < size; i = i + 1) {
      TreeNode curr = queue.poll();
      currList.add(curr.key);
      if (curr.left != null) {
        queue.offer(curr.left);
      }
      if (curr.right != null) {
        queue.offer(curr.right);
      }
    }
    result.add(currList);
  }
  return result;
}

Time: O(n)
Space: O(最寬層長度n)

public class Test {
  public static void main(String args[]) {
    TreeNode n1 = new TreeNode(1);
    TreeNode n2 = new TreeNode(2);
    TreeNode n3 = new TreeNode(3);
    TreeNode n4 = new TreeNode(4);
    TreeNode n5 = new TreeNode(5);
    n1.left = n2;
    n2.right = n3;
    n3.left = n4;
    n4.right = n5;
    Solution sol = new Solution();
    sol.printByLevel(n1);
  }
}

class TreeNode {
  int value;
  TreeNode left;
  TreeNode right;
  public TreeNode(int v) {
    value = v;
  }
}

class Solution {
  public void printByLevel(TreeNode root) {
    Queue<TreeNode> q = new ListedList<>();
    q.offer(root);
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
      int size = q.size();
      for (int i = 0; i < size; i = i + 1) {
        TreeNode curr = q.poll();
        System.out.print(curr.value + " ");
        if (curr.left != null) {
          q.offer(curr.left);
        }
        if (curr.right != null) {
          q/offer(curr.right);
        }
      }
      System.out.println("");
    }
  }
}

經典例題2

Determine whether a binary tree is a complete binary tree

boolean seenNull = true;
  1. In the order of BFS, if we encounter a node with missing children, then all following nodes must have no children
  2. The first node which has missing children must either have no children or has only a left child.

Solution:

  1. If a node has right child but not left child, false
  2. In the order of BFS: if a node starts to have missing child, all nodes after it must have no child! (in this example, 4)
public class Solution {
  public boolean isCompleted(TreeNode root) {
    if (root == null) {
      return true;
    }
    Queue<TreeNode> queue = new ListedList<>();
    queue.offer(root);
    //boolean visited is needed? -> no
    boolean metNull = false;
    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
      TreeNode cur = queue.poll();  //curr -> generates neighbors
      if (cur.left == null && cur.right != null) {
        return false;
      }
      if (metNull && (cur.left != null || cur.right != null)) {
        return false;
      }
      if (cur.left == null || cur.right == null) {
        metNull = true;
      }
      if (cur.left != null) {
        queue.offer(cur.left);
      }
      if (cur.right != null) {
        queue.offer(cur.right);
      }
    }
    return true;
  }
}
